Neurocardiogenic syncope (also known as vasovagal syncope): This is the most common type of syncope, often triggered by emotional stress, pain, or prolonged standing.
Orthostatic hypotension: This is a sudden drop in blood pressure when standing up from a sitting or lying position.
Dehydration: This can lead to a decrease in blood volume, which can cause hypotension and syncope.
Cardiac arrhythmias: This is an irregular heartbeat that can cause the heart to pump less effectively, leading to low blood pressure and syncope.
Hypoglycemia: This is low blood sugar, which can cause the body to release hormones that can cause hypotension and syncope.
Adrenal insufficiency: This is a condition in which the adrenal glands do not produce enough hormones, which can lead to hypotension and syncope.
Sepsis: This is a serious infection that can cause a drop in blood pressure and syncope.
Anaphylaxis: This is a severe allergic reaction that can cause a drop in blood pressure and syncope.
Internal bleeding: This can cause a drop in blood pressure and syncope.
Medication side effects: Some medications can cause hypotension and syncope as a side effect.
